plex and contradictory regime that maintains significant legal and bureaucratic silos. Azar Masoumi explains why state-controlled refugee protection persists despite its many failures, not only in Canada but globally. This rigorous study deftly argues that the paradoxical interplay between refugee law and claim-processing bureaucracies is symptomatic of a larger illogic: reliance on the exclusivist mechanisms of the nation-state to ensure the universal application of rights. Ultimately, this book illuminates just how this paradox has turned refugee protection into an unfulfilled promise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aRefugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311140824840uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486873040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774868730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774868730/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-140824-8  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles